How it works:

During cold start, prover keys are copied to /tmp folder from S3 (I use [S3File](https://github.com/dfstio/minanft-api/blob/master/src/storage/s3.ts) class):
```typescript
export async function loadCache(
  cacheBucket: string,
  folder: string,
  files: string[]
): Promise<void> {
  const existingFiles = await listFiles(folder);
  for (const file of files) {
    if (!existingFiles.includes(file)) {
      try {
        const s3File = new S3File(cacheBucket, file);
        const data = await s3File.get();
        await fs.writeFile(`${folder}/${file}`, data.Body);
      } catch (error) {
        console.log(`error downloading ${file}`, error);
      }
    } else {
    }
  }
}

export async function listFiles(folder: string): Promise<string[]> {
  try {
    const files = await fs.readdir(folder);
    console.log("files", files.length);
    return files;
  } catch (error) {
    console.log(`"Folder ${folder} not found.creating...`);
    try {
      await fs.mkdir(folder);
      const files = await fs.readdir(folder);
      console.log("files", files.length);
      return files;
    } catch (error) {
      console.log(`"Error creating folder ${folder}`, error);
      return [];
    }
  }
}
```

Using the [EFS filesystem](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/configuration-filesystem.html) mounted to the AWS lambda instance is possible as an alternative to using /tmp folder. EFS is slower than /tmp, but using it removes the need to copy prover keys from S3 to /tmp during cold start.

The default size of /tmp folder is 512 MB, so you need to increase it by setting the ephemeralStorageSize parameter:
```
  mint:
    handler: minanft.mint
    timeout: 900
    memorySize: 3008
    ephemeralStorageSize: 4096

```

When compiling, you need to save the verification key to the static variable and call compile() only in case this static variable is undefined:
```typescript
static updateVerificationKey: string | undefined;
static cache: Cache | undefined;
…
public static setCacheFolder(folder: string = "./nftcache"): void {
    MinaNFT.cache = Cache.FileSystem(folder);
}

public static async compile(): Promise<VerificationKey> {
    const options = MinaNFT.cache ? { cache: MinaNFT.cache! } : undefined;
    if (MinaNFT.updateVerificationKey === undefined) {
      console.time("MinaNFTMetadataUpdate compiled");
      await Key.compile(options);
      const { verificationKey } = await MinaNFTMetadataUpdate.compile(options);
      console.timeEnd("MinaNFTMetadataUpdate compiled");
      MinaNFT.updateVerificationKey = verificationKey;
    }
    …
}
```

then put it all together on AWS lambda:
```typescript
import nftfiles from "./nftfiles.json";

const nftCacheDir = "/tmp/nft-cache";
await loadCache(PROVER_KEYS_BUCKET!, nftCacheDir, nftfiles);
MinaNFT.setCacheFolder(nftCacheDir);

console.time("compiled");
await MinaNFT.compile();
console.timeEnd("compiled");

```

